I am conducting research to see what kind of people tend to vote. My goal is to see if particular characteristics of a person leads them to have a certain voter outcome. I will be studying the relationship of these variables through the 2016 ANES dataset, otherwise known as the American National Election Studies in the recent Trump-Clinton election.

Does Gender Effect Which Canidate a Person Votes For?

library(ggplot2)
anes2016 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Clinton16, y=voted2016,fill=factor(female))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack")+
  scale_fill_discrete(name="Gender",
                         breaks=c("0", "1"),
                         labels=c("Male", "Female")) +
  ggtitle("How Gender Effects Presidential Voting in the 2016 Election")+
  xlab("Trump Support              Clinton Support")+
  ylab("Number of Voters")
## Warning: Removed 1096 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

Above I have created a graph that shows the relationship between gender, presidential prefrence, and number of votes in the election. As you can see more females and males voted for Trump during the 2016 election. I can conclude that both more females voted for Trump than Clinton although the data was almost equal. For males there was a significant difference between men voting for Trump versus Clinton.

Does Education Levels Effect Voter Turnout?

anes2016 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=educ, y=voted2016)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack")+
  ggtitle("Relationship between Education and Voting in the Election")+
  xlab("Level of Education")+
  ylab("Number of Voters")+
  scale_x_continuous(limits =c(0,5))
## Warning: Removed 1121 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

The graph above shows the relationship between education and voting in the 2016 election. As you can see when the level of education was at 3 which refers to completing 4 years of college with a dimpolma, the voter turnout was the highest.

Does Gender Skew Your Political Party a Certain Way?

library(ggplot2)
anes2016 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=female, y=voted2016,fill=factor(Dem))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "stack")+
  scale_fill_discrete(name="Political Party",
                         breaks=c("0", "1"),
                         labels=c("Republican", "Democrat")) +
  ggtitle("Poltical Party Relationships with Gender and Voter Turnout")+
  xlab("Male Voters                         Female Voters")+
  ylab("Number of Voters") 
## Warning: Removed 1132 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

In the graph above you can conlude that in the 2016 election the majoirty of woman tend to be democratic voters. Males voters tend to remain more republican. My data is not drastically different therefore I cannot conclude that a specific gender will automatically skew your political outcome.
